        "basic_text_UHQbdb": {
          "type": "basic_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p><em>I wasn’t trying to biohack my sleep. I was just tired of being exhausted.</em></p><p>For years, my nights followed the same frustrating pattern.</p><p>I’d feel tired around 9 or 10pm. I’d get into bed at a reasonable time.</p><p>And then… nothing.</p><p>My body was exhausted, but my mind felt wide awake.</p><p>I’d lie there scrolling, watching videos, replying to texts — telling myself I’d put my phone down “in five minutes.” An hour would pass. Sometimes two.</p><p>When I finally fell asleep, it didn’t feel deep.</p><p>And in the morning, I woke up groggy, unfocused, and already behind.</p><p>Sound familiar?</p><h3><strong>The Part No One Talks About</strong></h3><p>I assumed this was just normal.</p><p>Everyone uses screens at night.</p><p>Everyone feels tired but wired.</p><p>Everyone struggles with sleep now.</p><p>But one night, after another restless evening, I started digging into <em>why</em> this was happening.</p><p>Not supplements.</p><p>Not routines.</p><p>Not meditation apps.</p><p>Light.</p><p>Specifically, <strong>artificial light</strong>.</p><h3><strong>What Artificial Light Was Doing to Me (Without Me Realizing It)</strong></h3><p>Screens, overhead LEDs, and indoor lighting don’t shut off when the day ends.</p><p>They keep sending “daytime” signals to your brain long after your body wants to rest.</p><p>I learned that certain wavelengths of light — especially blue and blue-green light — are shown in research to:</p><p></p><ul><li>Keep your brain alert<br/></li><li>Suppress melatonin<br/></li><li>Delay the natural wind-down process<br/></li></ul><p>So even though I <em>felt</em> tired, my nervous system was still stuck in day mode.</p><p>That explained everything.</p><h3><strong>Why “Regular” Blue Light Glasses Didn’t Work</strong></h3><p>I’d actually tried blue light glasses before.</p><p>They were clear. Barely noticeable.</p><p>And honestly? They didn’t change much.</p><p>Screens still felt sharp.</p><p>My mind still felt wired.</p><p>Sleep still took forever.</p><p>That’s when I realized something important:</p><p>Most blue light glasses are designed for <strong>daytime comfort</strong>, not nighttime recovery.</p><p>They don’t reduce <em>enough</em> of the light that actually keeps your brain stimulated at night.</p><h3><strong>The Glasses That Finally Made a Difference</strong></h3><p>That’s when I came across <strong>Parlay’s Sleep Enhancer Lens</strong>.</p><p>At first, I was skeptical.</p><p>They were visibly warmer than anything I’d worn before.</p><p>But after a few nights, the difference was obvious.</p><p>Screens felt softer.</p><p>My eyes relaxed instead of feeling tense.</p><p>And for the first time in a long time, my body actually started to slow down at night.</p><p>I wasn’t forcing sleep anymore.</p><p>It just… happened.</p><h3><strong>What Changed for Me</strong></h3><p>Within the first week, I noticed:</p><p></p><ul><li>I stopped feeling wired late at night<br/></li><li>Falling asleep took noticeably less time<br/></li><li>My sleep felt deeper and more consistent<br/></li><li>I woke up feeling clearer, not foggy<br/></li><li>The biggest surprise?</li></ul><p>I didn’t change my routine.</p><p>Same phone.</p><p>Same TV.</p><p>Same habits.</p><p>The only difference was <strong>reducing the stimulation from artificial light</strong>.</p><h3><strong>Why the Sleep Enhancer Lens Works</strong></h3><p>The Sleep Enhancer Lens is designed specifically for evening and nighttime use.</p><p>Instead of lightly filtering light, it <strong>reduces a broader range of stimulating wavelengths</strong> from screens and indoor lighting — the ones shown to interfere with sleep.</p><p>That creates a calmer visual environment, which helps your nervous system recognize that it’s time to slow down.</p><p>It’s not magic.</p><p>It’s removing the thing that was quietly keeping me awake.</p><h3><strong>The Results Speak for Themselves</strong></h3><p>Based on published light and sleep research and real customer experience:</p><p></p><ul><li><strong>Up to 99%</strong> reduction of blue-green light from screens<br/></li><li><strong>50–60% less</strong> melatonin suppression compared to no lens<br/></li><li><strong>20–40 minutes faster</strong> time to fall asleep after evening screen use<br/></li><li>Most users report feeling <strong>less overstimulated at night</strong><br/></li></ul><p><em>Individual results vary, but the pattern is consistent.</em></p><h3><strong>Who These Glasses Are For</strong></h3><p>If you:</p><p></p><ul><li>Feel tired but wired at night<br/></li><li>Struggle to fall asleep after screen use<br/></li><li>Wake up feeling unrefreshed<br/></li><li>Don’t want to overhaul your routine<br/></li></ul><p>These are worth trying.</p><h3><strong>A Small Change That Actually Mattered</strong></h3><p>I didn’t need a new bedtime ritual.</p><p>I didn’t need another supplement.</p><p>I just needed less stimulation where it mattered most.</p><p>The Sleep Enhancer Lens didn’t fix my sleep by adding something new.</p><p>It fixed my sleep by <strong>removing what was getting in the way</strong>.</p>",
